SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 810
By Massey
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of James "Jim" Moore Hart
of Knoxville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of James "Jim" Moore Hart of Knoxville; and
WHEREAS, Jim Hart was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, born in Knoxville, Mr. Hart attended Webb School of Knoxville and was a
member of the school's first graduating class; he went on to graduate from Davidson College in
1965; and
WHEREAS, during his sophomore year, Jim Hart met Jan Cummins, a student at Sullins
College in Bristol, Virginia, and married her shortly thereafter; this began a partnership that
would span nearly sixty-four years; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Hart's family had deep roots in the broadcasting and civic life of
Knoxville; John Hart, Mr. Hart's father, helped the WBIR founder, Jesse W. Birdwell, start the
station on AM radio in 1941; John Hart later became part of the station's original television
ownership group and was WBIR's general manager when it launched on TV in 1956; and
WHEREAS, Jim Hart was by his father's side in the station's early days and began his
own career as a sales executive at WBIR; he held general manager roles for television stations
in Winston-Salem, North Carolina, and Cincinnati, Ohio, before returning to Knoxville as general
manager for WBIR in 1981, serving in the position for nearly thirteen years; and
WHEREAS, while serving as general manager, Mr. Hart developed WBIR's "Straight
from the Heart" brand, which continues as the station's motto today; he also launched "The
Heartland Series," a longtime award-winning program that shared the stories of the Smokies
SJR0810
013262
- 1 -

and Appalachian culture and supported one of his main missions of celebrating the people of
East Tennessee; and
WHEREAS, in 1994, Jim Hart left WBIR and began leading several television and radio
stations as president of Multimedia, Inc.; he later served as senior vice president of Scripps-
Howard and then vice president for the E.W. Scripps Company, where he oversaw operations at
thirteen television affiliates across the country; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Hart retired from broadcasting at the age of sixty in 2001; throughout his
career, colleagues and staff consistently described him as a respected and supportive leader
who earned the loyalty of those with whom he worked; and
WHEREAS, upon retiring, Jim Hart began a second career in nonprofit leadership; in
2002, he began serving as president of Friends of the Smokies, playing a critical role in building
enduring fundraising events and advocacy efforts to preserve and protect the Great Smoky
Mountains National Park; under his leadership, Friends of the Smokies created the specialty
license plate program that raises millions of dollars for the park each year; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his love for East Tennessee and the Smoky Mountains, Mr.
Hart was a lifelong Tennessee Volunteers football fan and followed the program faithfully
throughout his life; and
WHEREAS, Jim Hart was deeply devoted to his family, and he always endeavored to
remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Hart is survived by his wife of nearly sixty-four years, Jan Hart; children,
Jennifer Hart (Bob Cook), James M. (Catherine) Hart II, John Hart (Alicia Renfroe); three
grandchildren, Leah, Cassie, and Christopher Hart; sister, Anne Hart; and niece, Katherine
(Jason Strickland); and a host of colleagues and friends; and
WHEREAS, Jim Hart was a passionate soul, who invested deeply and with his whole
heart in things he loved; he greatly impacted the lives of those who were blessed to know him,
and he leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in public life, compassion and
loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen endeavors; and
- 2 - 013262

WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of James "Jim" Moore Hart,
reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family, friends, and colleagues of Mr. Hart.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
